Problem 1:

Using the ozone data, fit a model with O3 as the response and temp, humidity and ibh as predictors. Use the Box–Cox method to determine the best transformation on the response.

Solution:

We will fit a model with O3 as the response, and temp, humidity and ibh as predictors. We have,

lmod <- lm(O3 ~ temp + humidity + ibh, data=ozone)
summary(lmod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = O3 ~ temp + humidity + ibh, data = ozone)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -11.5291  -3.0137  -0.2249   2.8239  13.9303 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -1.049e+01  1.616e+00  -6.492 3.16e-10 ***
## temp         3.296e-01  2.109e-02  15.626  < 2e-16 ***
## humidity     7.738e-02  1.339e-02   5.777 1.77e-08 ***
## ibh         -1.004e-03  1.639e-04  -6.130 2.54e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.524 on 326 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.684,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.6811 
## F-statistic: 235.2 on 3 and 326 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
plot(lmod)

We notice that there is strong indications of non-constant variance of the error and nonlinear structure in the residuals. We will perform a Box-Cox transformation on the response “O3” to see if this eliminates the issues.

boxcox(lmod, plotit=T, lambda=seq(0,1,by=0.1))

With respect to the Box-Cox \(95\%\) condidence interval, we see that the transformation by \(y\mapsto y^{1/4}\) or \(y\mapsto y^{1/3}\) are both plausible values for a transformation, and we securely rule out the null mapping.

We compare thus the transformation by the quartic and cubic roots:

lmod <- lm(O3^(1/4) ~ temp + humidity + ibh, data=ozone)
summary(lmod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = O3^(1/4) ~ temp + humidity + ibh, data = ozone)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -0.5433 -0.1084  0.0091  0.1247  0.4933 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  9.137e-01  6.184e-02  14.774  < 2e-16 ***
## temp         1.307e-02  8.070e-04  16.192  < 2e-16 ***
## humidity     2.977e-03  5.124e-04   5.810 1.48e-08 ***
## ibh         -4.849e-05  6.269e-06  -7.734 1.31e-13 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.1731 on 326 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7152, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7126 
## F-statistic: 272.9 on 3 and 326 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
plot(lmod)

lmod <- lm(O3^(1/3) ~ temp + humidity + ibh, data=ozone)
summary(lmod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = O3^(1/3) ~ temp + humidity + ibh, data = ozone)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -0.83199 -0.16870  0.01175  0.19914  0.79844 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  7.625e-01  9.926e-02   7.682 1.85e-13 ***
## temp         2.116e-02  1.295e-03  16.338  < 2e-16 ***
## humidity     4.879e-03  8.225e-04   5.933 7.61e-09 ***
## ibh         -7.693e-05  1.006e-05  -7.645 2.36e-13 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.2778 on 326 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7175, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7149 
## F-statistic:   276 on 3 and 326 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
plot(lmod)

As both transformations appear to deal with the nonlinearity in the residuals and the non-constant variance, both seem appropriate. We might favor the quartic root due to the lower standard error, but the difference overall is negligible.

Problem 2:

Using the fat dataset, fit a model with brozek as the response and age, weight, height and the body circumfrence measurements as predictors. Then simplify the saturated model using each of:

  1. Backward eliminaton
  2. AIC
  3. Adjusted \(R^2\)
  4. Mallow’s \(C_p\)

as a criterion for model selection. Discuss the differences in the selected models (if any).

Solution:

We will select a model for the fat data using each of the below:

Backward selection:

Here we will fit the model with all explanatory variables and work our way backwards to a smaller model with an initial choice of \(\alpha_\mathrm{crit}=5\%\):

AIC

Apologies, this was a typo! I wanted to evaluate the BIC, due to the fact that this is a standard output of the regsubsets function.

Here we will use the “regsubsets” of the “leaps” library to perform an exhaustive search over the models. In order to perform exhaustive search with more than 8 predictors, we have to use the keyword argument nv and set this to the total number of predictors. In particular, we get

sum_fat <-summary(regsubsets(brozek ~ age + weight + neck + chest + abdom + hip + thigh + knee + ankle + biceps + forearm + wrist, data=fat, nv=12))

R square

We can also make a selection based on the adjusted \(R^2_a\) as follows:

plot(c(1:12),sum_fat$adjr2, xlab = "Number of predictors", ylab="Adjusted R square")

rsquare <- sum_fat$adjr2
which(rsquare==max(rsquare))
## [1] 8

Here we find that the adjusted \(R^2_a\) attains a maximum value for the model including age, weight, neck, abdom, thigh, forearm and wrist.

lm_r_square <- lm(brozek ~ age + weight + neck + abdom + thigh + forearm + wrist, data=fat)
summary(lm_r_square)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = brozek ~ age + weight + neck + abdom + thigh + forearm +

Mallow’s Cp

Finally, we study the fit using Mallow’s Cp statistic. Here, numbers around the line \(C_p =\) “number of parameters” are favored, but we always favor smaller models and ones with \(C_p\) value under the line. Here the best choice is with 8 explanatory variables (9 parameters).

plot(c(2:13),sum_fat$cp, xlab = "Number of parameters", ylab="Mallows Cp")
abline(0,1)

CP <- sum_fat$cp
which(CP == min(CP))
## [1] 8
Discussion

Between the methods, we find two different groups of outcomes: (i) the smaller models favored by the BIC and the backward elimination, and (ii) the larget models favored by the \(R_a^2\) and Mallow’s \(C_p\). In the first case (i), we obtain different but very similar models in which weight, forearm and abdom are all included. The two models differ therin only by the choice of neck versus wrist, but both models only have predictors at \(5\%\) significance. The distinction between the two should be based on the diagnostics, as their \(R_a^2\) scores extremely close.

On the other hand, both Mallow’s \(C_p\) and \(R_a^2\) converge on the 8 predictor model. Both of the models chosen in group (i) are embedded submodels of the 8 predictor model, and their F-test comparisons with ANOVA are given by,

anova(lm_BIC, lm_r_square)

In both cases, we reject the null at \(5\%\) significance. The model we favor should be decided in large part by the diagnostics and which model is performing better with respect to our assumptions If more than one model is comparable, we might favor the 8 predictor model for prediction purposes, but favor the 4 predictor model(s) for explanation purposes due to the simplicity (and because these are embedded sub-models).
